Part 1

a) Illustrate the characteristics of the statistical model for dealing with the Dugongs data. Lengths (Yi) and ages (xi) of 27 dugongs (see cows) captured off the coast of Queensland have been recorded and the following (non linear) regression model is considered in Carlin and Gelfand (1991).

This, presented below, is a nonlinear model based on data about the height and age of dugongs. The number of measurements is 27 and the data are modeled as a non-linear growth model.

\(Y_i \sim \mathcal{N(\mu_i,\tau)}\) where \(\mu_i = f(x_i)= \alpha -\beta \gamma^{x_i}\), with \(i= 1,...,27\)

b) Derive the corresponding likelihood function

Likelihood function: \[\begin{align} L(\alpha,\beta,\gamma,\tau|y,x) = \prod_{i=1}^n \frac{1}{\Big(2\pi \tau^2\Big)^{\frac{1}{2}}} exp\bigg\{-\frac{(y_i-\mu_i)^2}{2\tau^2} \bigg\}\mathbb{1}_{(1, \infty)}(\alpha)\mathbb{1}_{(1, \infty)}(\beta)\mathbb{1}_{(0,1)}(\gamma)\mathbb{1}_{(0, \infty)}(\tau^2) = \end{align}\]

\[\begin{align} = \frac{1}{\Big(2\pi \tau^2\Big)^{\frac{n}{2}}} exp\bigg\{-\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n}(y_i-\mu_i)^2}{2\tau^2} \bigg\} \mathbb{1}_{(1, \infty)}(\alpha)\mathbb{1}_{(1, \infty)}(\beta)\mathbb{1}_{(0,1)}(\gamma)\mathbb{1}_{(0, \infty)}(\tau^2)= \end{align}\]

\[\begin{align} = \frac{1}{\Big(2\pi \tau^2\Big)^{\frac{n}{2}}} exp\bigg\{-\frac{\sum(y_i-\alpha+\beta \gamma^{x_i})^2}{2\tau^2} \bigg\} \end{align}\]

c) Write down the expression of the joint prior distribution of the parameters at stake and illustrate your suitable choice for the hyperparameters.

We can write the joint as the product of the following blocks:

\[\begin{align} \pi(\alpha) = \frac{1}{\sqrt(2\pi\sigma_\alpha^2)} e^{-\frac{\alpha}{2\sigma_\alpha^2}}\mathbb{1}_{(1, \infty)}(\alpha) \longrightarrow e^{-\frac{\alpha}{2\sigma_\alpha^2}}\mathbb{1}_{(1, \infty)}(\alpha) \end{align}\]

\[\begin{align} \pi(\beta) = \frac{1}{\sqrt(2\pi\sigma_\beta^2)} e^{-\frac{\beta}{2\sigma_\beta^2}}\mathbb{1}_{(1, \infty)}(\beta) \longrightarrow e^{-\frac{\beta}{2\sigma_\beta^2}}\mathbb{1}_{(1, \infty)}(\beta) \end{align}\]

\[\begin{align} \pi(\gamma) = Unif(0,1)(\gamma) \end{align}\]

\[\begin{align} \pi(\tau^2) = InvGamma(a,b) = \frac{b^a}{\Gamma(a)}\tau^{-2(a+1)} e^{-\frac{b}{\tau^2}}\mathbb{1}_{(1, \infty)}(\gamma)\longrightarrow \tau^{-2(a+1)}e^{-\frac{b}{\tau^2}}\mathbb{1}_{(0, \infty)} \end{align}\]

\[\begin{align} \boxed{\pi(\theta) = \pi(\alpha) \cdot \pi(\beta) \cdot \pi(\gamma) \cdot \pi(\tau^2) = e^{-\frac{\alpha}{2\sigma_\alpha^2}} \cdot e^{-\frac{\beta}{2\sigma_\beta^2}} \cdot \mathbb{1}_{(0, 1)}(\gamma) \cdot \tau^{-2(a+1)}e^{-\frac{b}{\tau^2}}} \end{align}\]

d) Derive the functional form (up to proportionality constants) of all full-conditionals

\(\alpha\)

\[\begin{align} \pi(\alpha | \beta, \gamma,\tau^2,x,y) = \frac{1}{(2\pi\tau^2)^{\frac{n}{2}}} exp\{- \frac{1}{2\tau^2} \sum_{i=1}^{n} (y_i-\mu_i)^2 \} \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\sigma_{\alpha}^2}} exp\{ - \frac{\alpha^2}{2\sigma_{\alpha}^2} \}\mathbb{1}_{(1, \infty)}(\alpha) \end{align}\]

\[\begin{align} = \frac{1}{(2\pi\tau^2)^{\frac{n}{2}}} exp\{ - \frac{1}{2\tau^2} \sum_{i=1}^{n} (y_i -\alpha + \beta\gamma^{x_i})^2 \} \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\sigma_{\alpha}^2}} exp\{- \frac{\alpha^2}{2\sigma_{\alpha}^2} \} \mathbb{1}_{(1, \infty)}(\alpha) \end{align}\]

\[\begin{align} \propto exp\{ - \frac{1}{2\tau^2} \sum_{i=1}^{n} (y_i -\alpha + \beta\gamma^{x_i})^2 \} exp\{- \frac{\alpha^2}{2\sigma_{\alpha}^2}\} \mathbb{1}_{(1, \infty)}(\alpha) \end{align}\]

\[\begin{align} \propto exp\{ - \frac{\alpha^2}{2\sigma_{\alpha}^2} - \frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n} (\alpha^2 - 2\alpha y_i -2\alpha\beta\gamma^{x_i})}{2\tau^2}\} \mathbb{1}_{(1, \infty)}(\alpha) \end{align}\]

\[\begin{align} \propto exp\{- \frac{\alpha^2}{2} \frac{\tau^2 + n\sigma_{\alpha}^2}{\sigma_{\alpha}^2 \tau^2} + \alpha \frac{\sigma_{\alpha}^2 \sum_{i=1}^{n}(y_i+\beta\gamma^{x_i}) }{ \sigma_{\alpha}^2 \tau^2} \} \mathbb{1}_{(1, \infty)}(\alpha) \end{align}\]

\[\begin{align} \boxed{\pi(\alpha | \beta, \gamma,\tau^2,x,y) \sim \mathcal{N} (\frac{\sigma_{\alpha}^2 \sum_{i=1}^{n}(y_i+\beta\gamma^{x_i})}{\tau^2 + n\sigma_{\alpha}^2}, \frac{\sigma_{\alpha}^2 \tau^2}{\tau^2 + n\sigma_{\alpha}^2} )\mathbb{1}_{(1, \infty)}} \end{align}\]

\(\beta\)

\[\begin{align} \pi(\beta | \alpha, \gamma,\tau^2,x,y) = \frac{1}{(2\pi\tau^2)^{\frac{n}{2}}} exp\{- \frac{1}{2\tau^2} \sum_{i=1}^{n} (yi-\mu_i)^2 \} \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\sigma_{\beta}^2}} exp\{ - \frac{\beta^2}{2\sigma_{\beta}^2} \}\mathbb{1}_{(1, \infty)}(\beta) \end{align}\]

\[\begin{align} = \frac{1}{(2\pi\tau^2)^{\frac{n}{2}}} exp\{ - \frac{1}{2\tau^2} \sum_{i=1}^{n} (y_i -\alpha + \beta\gamma^{x_i})^2 \} \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\sigma_{\beta}^2}} exp\{- \frac{\beta^2}{2\sigma_{\beta}^2} \} \mathbb{1}_{(1, \infty)}(\beta) \end{align}\]

\[\begin{align} \propto exp\{ - \frac{1}{2\tau^2} \sum_{i=1}^{n} (y_i -\alpha + \beta\gamma^{x_i})^2 \} exp\{- \frac{\beta^2}{2\sigma_{\beta}^2} \mathbb{1}_{(1, \infty)}(\beta) \} \end{align}\]

\[\begin{align} \propto exp\{ - \frac{\beta^2}{2\sigma_{\beta}^2} - \frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n} (\beta^{2}\gamma^{2x_i} -2\beta y_{i}\gamma^{x_i} -2\alpha\beta\gamma^{x_i})}{2\tau^2}\} \mathbb{1}_{(1, \infty)}(\beta) \end{align}\]

\[\begin{align} \propto exp\{- \frac{\beta^2}{2} \frac{\tau^2 + \sigma_{\beta}^2 \sum_{i=1}^{n} \gamma^{2x_i}}{\sigma_{\beta}^2 \tau^2} + \beta \frac{\sigma_{\beta}^2 \sum_{i = 1}^{n} \gamma^{x_i}(\alpha - y_i) }{\sigma_{\beta}^2 \tau^2} \} \mathbb{1}_{(1, \infty)}(\beta) \end{align}\]

\[\begin{align} \boxed{\pi(\beta | \alpha, \gamma,\tau^2,x,y) \sim \mathcal{N}{(1,\infty)} (\frac{\sigma_{\beta}^2 \sum_{i = 1}^{n} \gamma^{x_i}(\alpha - y_i)}{\tau^2 + \sigma_{\beta}^2 \sum_{i = 1}^{n} \gamma^{2x_i}} , \frac{\sigma_{\beta}^2 \tau^2}{\tau^2 + \sigma_{\beta}^2 \sum_{i = 1}^{n} \gamma^{2x_i}} )\mathbb{1}_{(1, \infty)}} \end{align}\]

\(\gamma\)

\[\begin{align} \pi(\gamma | \alpha, \beta,\tau^2,x,y) = \frac{1}{(2\pi\tau^2)^{\frac{n}{2}}} exp\{-\frac{1}{2\tau^2}\sum_{i=1}^{n} (y_i - \mu_i)^2\} \mathbb{1}_{(0, 1)}(\gamma)= \end{align}\]

\[\begin{align} = \frac{1}{(2\pi\tau^2)^{\frac{n}{2}}} exp\{-\frac{1}{2\tau^2}\sum_{i=1}^{n} (y_i - \alpha + \beta\gamma^{x_i})^2\} \mathbb{1}_{[0, 1]}(\gamma) \end{align}\]

\[\begin{align} \boxed{\pi(\gamma | \alpha, \beta,\tau^2,x,y) \propto exp\{-\frac{1}{2\tau^2}\sum_{i=1}^{n} (y_i - \alpha + \beta\gamma^{x_i})^2\} \mathbb{1}_{(0, 1)}(\gamma)} \end{align}\]

\(\tau^2\)

\[\begin{align} \pi(\tau^2 | \alpha, \beta,\gamma,x,y) = \frac{1}{\tau^{2(\frac{n}{2}) } \tau^{2(\alpha +1)} } exp\{-\frac{\frac{1}{2} \sum_{i=1}^{n}(y_i -\alpha + \beta\gamma^{x_i})^2 -b }{ \tau^2}\}\mathbb{1}_{(0, 1)}(\tau^2) \end{align}\]

\[\begin{align} \frac{1}{\tau^{2(\frac{n}{2} + \alpha +1)}} exp\{- \frac{b + \frac{1}{2} \sum_{i=1}^{n}(y_i -\alpha + \beta\gamma^{x_i})^2}{\tau^2}\}\mathbb{1}_{[0, 1]}(\tau^2) \end{align}\]

\[\begin{align} \boxed{\pi(\tau^2 | \alpha, \beta,\gamma,x,y) \sim IG_{(0, \infty)}(\alpha + \frac{n}{2}, b + \frac{1}{2} \sum_{i=1}^{n}(y_i -\alpha + \beta\gamma^{x_i})^2)} \end{align}\]

e) Which distribution can you recognize within standard parametric families so that direct simulation from full conditional can be easily implemented?

The parameters \(\alpha\), \(\beta\) and \(\tau^2\) belong to a standard parametric families like Normal and Inverse-Gamma. The parameter \(\gamma\), does not belongs to a standard parametric family, for this reason i implemented Metropolis-Hastings algorithm.

f) Using a suitable Metropolis-within-Gibbs algorithm simulate a Markov chain (T = 10000) to approximate the posterior distribution for the above model
alpha[1] = 2
beta[1] = 2
gamma[1] = 0.5
tau_square[1] = 0.1


# full conditional gamma
full_cond_gamma = function(x,y,gamma, alpha, beta, tau_square) {
  return(exp(-1/(2*tau_square)*sum((y-alpha+beta*gamma^x)^2)))
}

metropolis.gibbs <- function(x, y,alpha, beta, gamma,tau_square,sigma_squared_a,sigma_squared_b,a,b,n,iterations) { 
for(t in 1:iterations) {
  # updating the t+1 th term of the alpha Markov chain
  alpha[t+1] = rnorm(1,(sigma_squared_a*sum(y+beta[t]*gamma[t]^x))/(n*sigma_squared_a+tau_square[t]),
                     sqrt((tau_square[t]*sigma_squared_a)/(n*sigma_squared_a + tau_square[t])))
  # updating the t+1 th term of the alpha Markov chain
  beta[t+1] = rnorm(1,(sigma_squared_b*sum((alpha[t+1]-y)*gamma[t]^x)) /
                      (sigma_squared_b*sum(gamma[t]^(2*x))+tau_square[t]),
                    sqrt((tau_square[t]*sigma_squared_b)/(sigma_squared_b*sum(gamma[t]^(2*x))+tau_square[t])))
#proposal is a float value taken from a uniform distribution. 
  proposal = runif(1,0,1)
#computing the probability given by the full conditional for the parameter gamma accordigly to the proposal generated.   
  prob = full_cond_gamma(x,y,proposal, alpha[t+1], beta[t+1], tau_square[t]) /
    full_cond_gamma(x,y,gamma[t], alpha[t+1], beta[t+1], tau_square[t])
#If the posterior probability is greater than the new value theta, the ratio of the probability 
#will be greater than 1 and we will always accept the new value of theta. 
#If the posterior probability is greater for the posterior value of theta we will not necessarily discard that value. 
  gamma[t+1] = ifelse(runif(1,0,1)<=prob, proposal, gamma[t])
  tau_square[t+1] = rinvgamma(1, n/2 + a,
                              b+1/2*sum((y-alpha[t+1]+beta[t+1]*(gamma[t+1]^x))^2))
}
  
coll <- list ("alpha" = alpha,"beta" = beta,"gamma" = gamma, "tau_square" = tau_square)
return (coll)
}

plotting.trace <- function(parameter,name,color){
plot(cumsum(parameter)/(1:length(parameter)), type="l",ylim = c(min(parameter), max(parameter)), ylab=" ",
      xlab="simulations",col=color, main = paste0(name))
abline(h=mean(parameter), col="grey1",lty=2)
}

c) Repeat the simulation for 500 times and record only the final state at time t = 1000 for each of the 500 simulated chains.Compute the relative frequency of the 500 final states. What distribution are you approximating in this way? Try to formalize the difference between this point and the previous point.
chain.final.state <- function(n,nsample,x0){

t_chain=rep(NA, n)
for (i in 1:n){

  chain=rep(NA,nsample+1)
  chain[1]=x0
  for(t in 1:nsample){
    chain[t+1]=sample(script_S,size=1,prob=tpm[chain[t],])
  }
  t_chain[i]=tail(chain,1)
}
return(t_chain)
}
chain.fin_x01 = chain.final.state(n=500,nsample=1000,x0=1)
rbind(prop.table(table(chain)),prop.table(table(chain.fin_x01)))
##              1         2         3
## [1,] 0.3856144 0.3416583 0.2727273
## [2,] 0.4000000 0.3140000 0.2860000
plot(chain.fin_x01,ylim=c(1,3), col="#2a6041", main = "Markov Chain", ylab= "", xlab= "number of iterations")

In this case we are, in contrast to the previous point in which we considered the whole Markov chain of the process, we are taking only the last state of 500 different chains. On the other hand, if the process is ergotic, the probability of different states (1,2,3 in this exercise) converges to the same distribution. Also, because we are taking the final values of each of the 500 Markov chains allows us to say that we are still taking a good approximation for our process, because we have already reached the stability stage of the process.

d) Compute the theoretical stationary distribution and explain how you have obtained it.

In this case (3 dimensional space), the stationary distribution can be found by solving the following linear system. \[\begin{align} \begin{pmatrix} p_{11} & p_{12}& p_{13}\\ p_{21} &p_{22} &p_{23}\\ p_{131} &p_{32}&p_{33} \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} \pi_1\\ \pi_2\\ \pi_3 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} \pi_1\\ \pi_2\\ \pi_3 \end{pmatrix} \end{align}\]

This matrix linear system can be written in a more compact way as following: \[\begin{align} P^{T}\pi=\pi \\ (P^{T}-\lambda I)\pi = 0 \end{align}\] Remembering that the only equation in which we are interested on, is the one that satisfy this property: \[\begin{align} \pi_1 + \pi_2 + \pi_3 = 1 \end{align}\]

At the end, we can solve the system finding the eigenvectors associated to the corresponding eingvalues.
